eanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Craon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Manx: variant of   Craine  .","English: variant of   Crane  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Craine","meanings":["Manx: shortened form of Gaelic <b>Mac (Giolla) Ciaráin</b> ‘son of (the devotee of) <i>Ciarán</i>’, a personal name based on a diminutive of Gaelic <i>ciar</i>, Manx <i>keeir</i> ‘black’. The place Ballacraine on the Isle of Man means ‘Craine's farm’."]}]},{"name":"Cecilia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."],"variants":[{"name":"Cecelia","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":80,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":89,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Cecilia de Craon was born about 1135, in Freiston, Lincolnshire, England, her father, Alan de Craon, Lord of Freiston, was 37 and her mother, Muriel de Beauchamp, was 32. She married William de Woodthorpe I in 1154, in Freiston, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in Alford, Lincolnshire, England."},"et":{"about 1135–":"umbes 1135–Surnud","1125–1188":"1125–1188","1135–Female":"1135–Surnud","1142–1196":"1142–1196","1180–Male":"1180–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1100–1155":"1100–1155","1105–1182":"1105–1182","1154":"1154","1142":"1142","1196":"1196","1182":"1182","1180":"1180","1215":"1215","1105":"1105","Cir 1180":"1180","1224":"1224","1125":"1125","1135":"1135","1155":"1155","1100":"1100","1188":"1188","about 1135":"umbes 1135","Alford, Lincolnshire, England":"Alford, Lincolnshire, England","Freiston, Lincolnshire, England":"Freiston, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Woodthorpe Hall, Alford, Lincolnshire, England":"Alford, Lincolnshire, England","Freiston, Boston, Lincolnshire, England":"Freiston, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1135–":"noin 1135–Kuollut","1125–1188